The launch of this new campaign, in line with the World Population Day, was followed by a referendum last week. This legislation does not criminalise persons who have difficulties in realising their sexual and reproductive rights, but makes it possible to easily recognise that there are several circumstances where an abortion implemented in a decent and human respect in hospitals and/or clinics.

“Statistics clearly show that the latest legal flexibilities regarding abortion have significantly reduced unwanted pregnancies in Seychelles Island, where laws allow the termination of pregnancy in the first trimester, up to six weeks from conception, when the pregnancy is a danger to the physical or mental health of the woman,” said Catherine Prayet Ngoile of the Maharagama Center for Mental Health Awareness. “It is critical to bear in mind that mental health care – like any other health care treatment is a choice and can be made by every individual.”

Whether legal or not, people who decide to undergo abortion are prone to having mental and physical disorders. This decision is not taken in haste and is meticulously considered. Several different elements can influence these decisions, starting with maternal ill-health and death of the fetus.
